  "prompt": "What is the difference between \"don't we verb\" and \" do we not verb\"?",
  "response": "Both \"don't we verb\" and \"do we not verb\" are interrogative constructions used to seek confirmation or agreement, but they have slight differences in tone and usage:\n\n1. \"Don't we verb\" (tag question):\n- More conversational and informal\n- Often used to seek agreement or confirmation\n- Suggests the speaker expects a \"yes\" answer\n- More common in spoken English\n- Example: \"We're going to the party, don't we?\"\n\n2. \"Do we not verb\" (direct question):\n- More formal and emphatic\n- Implies a more serious or deliberate questioning\n- Can express slight doubt or challenge\n- Less common in everyday speech\n- Example: \"Do we not have the right to speak freely?\"\n\nThe key differences are in tone, formality, and implied expectation. \"Don't we\" sounds more casual and assumes agreement, while \"Do we not\" sounds more formal and can suggest a more serious inquiry or potential disagreement.",
